      <!-- OBJECTIONS -->
      <div class="obj-title">Common Objections — What to Say</div>

      <div class="obj-list">

        <div class="obj-item">
          <div class="obj-q">
            <span class="obj-tag">Objection 1</span>
            "Will anyone actually send meals? What if my client sets this up and nothing happens?"
          </div>
          <div class="obj-a">
            <div class="obj-a-label">Your Response</div>
            <p>This is the most important objection to neutralize — because the value of YK lives entirely in coordinator activation.</p>
            <p><strong>Reframe the promise first:</strong> You're not selling "meals will show up." You're offering a tool the client's village can use when they want to help. The platform exists for people who already want to act — it gives them a specific, easy way to do it. Whether that village shows up depends on the relationships that already exist, not the platform.</p>
            <p><strong>Then give them the warm-start protocol:</strong> "For every client you activate, we recommend your own team member — the social worker, the doula, the care coordinator — claims the first date. One action primes the whole network. When someone sees one date is taken, they take another."</p>
            <p><strong>Then close with data:</strong> "In our pilot, the average kitchen had 4 coordinators claim dates within the first week of activation. We'll track that for every client you serve and report it back to you monthly."</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-item">
          <div class="obj-q">
            <span class="obj-tag">Objection 2</span>
            "Why would we pay for this when we could just tell families about MealTrain for free?"
          </div>
          <div class="obj-a">
            <div class="obj-a-label">Your Response</div>
            <p>MealTrain is a scheduling calendar. Someone still has to cook, shop, or coordinate a restaurant order manually. There's no payment, no delivery, no confirmation — just a sign-up sheet.</p>
            <p>YourKitchen is end-to-end. A coordinator picks a restaurant your client already loves, pays right there, and a meal shows up at their door. The client confirms by a single text reply before anything is charged. Nothing falls through the cracks.</p>
            <p><strong>The one-liner:</strong> "MealTrain tells people when to bring food. YourKitchen handles everything so they actually can — no matter where they live."</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-item">
          <div class="obj-q">
            <span class="obj-tag">Objection 3</span>
            "We don't have a budget for this right now."
          </div>
          <div class="obj-a">
            <div class="obj-a-label">Your Response</div>
            <p>Two options depending on the relationship:</p>
            <p><strong>Option A — Pilot first:</strong> "Then let's not talk about budget yet. Give me two clients for 30 days at no cost. If it improves their experience and you hear it from them directly, the budget conversation becomes easy. If it doesn't, you've lost nothing."</p>
            <p><strong>Option B — Reframe the cost:</strong> "Ten accounts for a year is under $1,200 — that's $100 a month to offer a differentiated care service to every client you serve in a life transition. Most orgs spend more than that on printed materials." Then stop talking. Let the number sit.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-item">
          <div class="obj-q">
            <span class="obj-tag">Objection 4</span>
            "Our clients are going through something really hard. We don't want to add anything to their plate."
          </div>
          <div class="obj-a">
            <div class="obj-a-label">Your Response</div>
            <p>This objection usually comes from hospice, bereavement, or oncology partners — and it's coming from a genuinely good place. Honor it before you answer it.</p>
            <p>"That's exactly why we built the confirmation step the way we did. The recipient gets a single text: 'Your village sent you dinner Tuesday at 6pm — reply Y to confirm or N to skip.' One letter. That's all they have to do. If they don't reply, nothing is charged and nothing is sent. They're never obligated. They're never surprised."</p>
            <p>"The coordinators carry the burden. The client just says yes or no."</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-item">
          <div class="obj-q">
            <span class="obj-tag">Objection 5</span>
            "What happens when the 90 days expire and the client still needs support?"
          </div>
          <div class="obj-a">
            <div class="obj-a-label">Your Response</div>
            <p>"Two options. First, you can reactivate a new slot for that client if their need continues — your pool just assigns them a fresh 90-day window. Second, if they want to continue independently, they can move to a personal Care+ account at $19.99/month. Either way, they're never stranded."</p>
            <p>"The 90-day window is designed to match the most acute phase of most life transitions. But the platform stays flexible for clients whose situations run longer."</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-item">
          <div class="obj-q">
            <span class="obj-tag">Objection 6</span>
            "How do we know your platform will still be around in a year?"
          </div>
          <div class="obj-a">
            <div class="obj-a-label">Your Response</div>
            <p>This one requires confidence, not defensiveness. Don't over-explain. Don't apologize for being early.</p>
            <p>"I'm the founder. I built this for my own family — my wife used it after our third child was born. This isn't a side project. The platform is live, payments are processing, and deliveries are happening today. I'm not going anywhere."</p>
            <p>"And honestly — that's an advantage for you right now. You're working directly with me, not a support ticket. If something doesn't work for your clients, I fix it. That's a level of responsiveness you won't get from any established platform."</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="obj-item" style="border-bottom: none;">
          <div class="obj-q">
            <span class="obj-tag">Objection 7</span>
            "Can we just refer clients to the app directly without buying a pool?"
          </div>
          <div class="obj-a">
            <div class="obj-a-label">Your Response</div>
            <p>"Absolutely — and I'd love that. If you want to be a referral partner first, let's start there. You share the link, your clients try it, and you see how it lands. No contract, no cost."</p>
            <p>"The Kitchen Pool model is for orgs that want to gift access to clients directly — so the client never has to pull out a credit card. It's a different level of care. But referral is a great place to start, and if it works, the conversation about the pool happens naturally."</p>
            <p>This keeps the door open. A referral partner who sees real results becomes a pool buyer. Don't force the close.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

